version: 1
display_name: VCFE-9X-000208 - The ESX host Secure Shell (SSH) daemon must not permit user environment settings.
global_description: |-
  SSH environment options potentially allow users to bypass access restriction in some configurations. Users must not be able to present environment options to the SSH daemon.
osfinger: []  # API/proxy-managed control; not tied to a minion OS grain
refs:
  disa_stig:
    - VCFE-9X-000208
  srg:
    - SRG-OS-000480-VMM-002000
  cci:
    - CCI-000366
  nist:
    - CM-6 b
benchmark_id:
  vcf9_vsphere_esx:
    type: custom
    desc: The ESX host Secure Shell (SSH) daemon must not permit user environment settings.
    control_id: VCFE-9X-000208
    scored: true
    profile:
      - default
    information: |-
      From an ESX shell, run the following command:

      # esxcli system ssh server config list -k permituserenvironment

      or

      From a PowerCLI command prompt while connected to the ESX host, run the following commands:

      $esxcli = Get-EsxCli -v2
      $esxcli.system.ssh.server.config.list.invoke() | Where-Object {$_.Key -eq 'permituserenvironment'}

      Example result:

      permituserenvironment no

      If "permituserenvironment" is not configured to "no", this is a finding.
    rationale: |-
      SSH environment options potentially allow users to bypass access restriction in some configurations. Users must not be able to present environment options to the SSH daemon.
    remediation: |-
      From an ESX shell, run the following command:

      # esxcli system ssh server config set -k permituserenvironment -v no

      or

      From a PowerCLI command prompt while connected to the ESX host, run the following commands:

      $esxcli = Get-EsxCli -v2
      $arguments = $esxcli.system.ssh.server.config.set.CreateArgs()
      $arguments.keyword = 'permituserenvironment'
      $arguments.value = 'no'
      $esxcli.system.ssh.server.config.set.Invoke($arguments)
